ce:section.ce:para:
The crystallite structure and phase composition of the prepared CdS samples were analyzed by XRD analysis as shown in Fig. 2
                        a. The peaks at 24.948, 26.547, 28.167, 36.643, 43.79, 47.93, 51.937, 66.93, 69.48 and 71.229 2θ values were due to the diffraction from the (100), (002), (101), (102), (110), (103), (112), (203), (210) and (211) planes of bare CdS NRs. In case of CQD@CdSNFs, irrespective to hydrothermal timing both the samples show a slight peak shift towards higher 2θ values at 25.048, 26.647, 28.396, 43.805, 48.038 and 52.087 for diffraction (100), (002), (101), (110), (103) and (112) planes respectively. This can be attributed due to presence of CQD on CdS surface. Moreover, a significant decrease in intensity of diffraction peaks can be observed and a few planes such as (102), (203), (210), (211) almost discerned. The diffraction patterns as shown can correspond to the hexagonal wurtzite CdS phase (JCPDS No. 01-077-2306 and 00-001-0783). The absence of any peak indexing to (200) plane of cubic zinc blende CdS, which proves the phase purity of CdS samples. Besides, all with the introduction of CQD, no additional peaks were noticed, which indicates the low doping concentration of CQD. The XRD pattern of CQD (
                           Fig S1
                        ) exhibited one peak centered at 2θ = 21° corresponding to (002) plane of carbon. The average crystal size, dislocation density and micro strain were obtained as structural parameters from XRD data (
                           S2.1
                        ).
